column1: Before 27 June 2020, will the weekly average contract interest rate for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages with conforming loan balances in the U.S. fall below 3.00%?
column6: ['Finance', 'Economic Indicators']

Initial forecast. Only 4 days left in forecast. Current crowd forecast is zero. Current interest rate is 3.3% (17 June)
Rates ticked higher. Since it is a weekly average, now no mathematical chance.

While mortgage rates are typically in lock-step with the 10-yr Treasury, there is substantial separation between the two right now. We've previously seen a 0.22 point drop week over week, and right now we would only need to see a 0.14 point drop to get below 3%. The harsh reality is that most investors are jittery enough, as seen by the current stock market, to jolt the mortgage market rate that much lower, even with an 8% delinquency rate.
July is quite possible, I don't think June. With demand holding steady, and very slightly improved jobs reports, I don't see it this week.

Currently 3.13% -- a drop of .14 would be a decline of at least 4% in just 10 days. Mortgage rates don't move that fast barring some extraordinary Fed action.

Regression on 10yr constant maturity on 30 year mortgage rates is holding steady. Beats have increased slightly since the Fed stepped in, but I think structural issues such as supply will keep a floor on rates until July. The quadratic model that better captures the relationship between the 10 year and mortgages in past crises is also holding up. Actuals are still coming in above the regression’s estimate.
Updating average of volatility model and linear model with latest data (sample size since beginning of year) [1]. Not sure why crowd forecast is so high.

The Financial Times article referenced below explains why the mortgage market has not been responding to the extremely low US Treasury rates. According to the MBA, 7.54% of loans are now in forbearance. Why would a loan originator take on 1000 new loans when chances are 75 of them will not make payments. Until the loan can be packaged and sold to Fannie Mae or another investor the originator is responsible for payments of principal, interest, taxes, and insurance. It's not an attractive proposition.

mortgage rates have never gone that low. No matter how many mortgages the Fed buys, there has to be a floor in a rational world. Unless the Fed buys all of them. Inflation may fluctuate, might be below 2% short term and above 2% long term, but around 2% is what a lender/investor is likely thinking since that is the Fed target. At 3% mortgage that would only leave 1% for profit and risk compensation. And a rational investor would be thinking higher than normal risk right now. Last count we were still at 3.45%, even with Fed purchases. It's not coming down another 50 basis points. Although, I do think a lot of things are going to go crazy, like oil going negative. No matter where the Fed puts the federal funds rate, the mortgage rate won't go that low. Firstly, even the banks are aware of inflation risk. Inflation currently at about 2% and even mainstream economists admit it may rise with all the money creation going on. Also, banks are now estimating as many as 39% of mortgages may default as unemployed people struggle to pay their bills. A lot of mortgages won't be paid April 1. Banks are not going to be free with their money. A week ago Fannie Mae just put out very severe limitations on underwriting loans for manufactured homes. Disclosure: I'm a real estate appraiser. and I noticed that the people on here that actually have comments to make all seem to be predicting a very low percentage.

Though Fed rates are falling, the market rates for mortgages don't necessarily follow the trend, and the market will still perceive risks in lending, despite the money pumped in by the Fed. Investors are not buying at a lower rate of return and lenders usually charge a higher interest, which maintains the rate at 3% level year round. Mortgage rates may fall below 3%, at some point, probably reaching as low as 2.8%, but this will not be sustained at a longer time.

I think an environment of falling interest rates driven by the fed implies that rates would fall. while there will be massive fed efforts to boost the economy and pump liquidity into the money supply, and even though some of that is explicitly targeting mortgage rates, I don't think it will be enough to overcome:

The Feds may continue pushing the interest rates down to offer cheap money as a stimulus. Large quantities of us may be jobless by May with no prospective re-employment opportunities, which translates to mass loan defaults and in turn leads to a negative market reaction that feeds the cycle by creating more layoffs. The solution is simple, but no one wants to see it.

I changed my mind on this. It has historically never been below 3.29%. CPI inflation is around 2.15%, and likely to rise with all the money printing and shortage of goods. The inflation rate sets a floor on the mortgage rate. Mortgage rates will never drop below inflation plus a certain risk & profit premium. Also all the rush of refinances are pushing rates up. The Fed dropped the Fed funds rate and mortgage rates actually went up due to demand.
I was wrong, and reconsidered my thinking.

During the great recession, the Fed benchmark rate was held at 0% between 2008 and 2015. The lowest the average 30-year Fixed-rate reached during that timeframe was 3.35% in November and December of 2012[1]. During that same timeframe, the 10-year Treasury Yield reached 1.626% and 1.742% respectively[2]. During the month of November, in 2012, Fannie Mae/Freddie Mac reported that there were 573,153 refinances processed. For the month of December, they reported 359,205 mortgages refinanced[3]. Also, during this time period banks were completing refinance applications in about 57 days [4].
